---
import IFSEntryLayout from '../../layouts/IFSEntryLayout.astro';
import IFSCanvas from '../../components/IFSCanvas.astro';

const t1 = "$$f_1(x,y) = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}\\begin{pmatrix}\\cos 45^\\circ & -\\sin 45^\\circ\\\\ \\sin 45^\\circ & \\cos 45^\\circ\\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix}x\\\\y\\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix}0.5 & -0.5\\\\0.5 & 0.5\\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix}x\\\\y\\end{pmatrix}$$";
const t2 = "$$f_2(x,y) = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}\\begin{pmatrix}\\cos 135^\\circ & -\\sin 135^\\circ\\\\ \\sin 135^\\circ & \\cos 135^\\circ\\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix}x\\\\y\\end{pmatrix} + \\begin{pmatrix}1\\\\0\\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix}-0.5 & 0.5\\\\-0.5 & -0.5\\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix}x\\\\y\\end{pmatrix} + \\begin{pmatrix}1\\\\0\\end{pmatrix}$$";
const dimFormula = "$$d \\approx 1.5236$$";
---
<IFSEntryLayout
  title="Dragon Curve — IFS Encyclopedia"
  description="The Dragon Curve is a space-filling fractal arising from two rotational contraction mappings."
  name="Dragon Curve"
  dimension="≈ 1.5236"
>
  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p>
    The <strong>Dragon Curve</strong> (also called the Heighway Dragon, after NASA physicist
    John Heighway who first studied it in the 1960s) is a self-similar fractal that can be
    constructed by repeatedly folding a strip of paper in half and unfolding it so each fold
    is at a right angle.
  </p>
  <p>
    As an IFS, the Dragon Curve is the attractor of two affine contractions, each a rotation
    by ±45° combined with a scaling by 1/√2. The resulting curve is continuous, non-self-
    intersecting, and tiles the plane.
  </p>

  <h2>Visualization</h2>
  <IFSCanvas id="dragon-curve" width={500} height={500} label="Dragon Curve" />

  <h2>Definition</h2>
  <p>The Dragon Curve is the attractor of two rotational contractions:</p>

  <h3>Transformation 1 — Rotation by +45°, scale 1/√2</h3>
  <p set:html={t1}></p>

  <h3>Transformation 2 — Rotation by +135°, scale 1/√2, translate (1,0)</h3>
  <p set:html={t2}></p>

  <h2>Properties</h2>
  <p>The Hausdorff dimension is:</p>
  <p set:html={dimFormula}></p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Contractivity ratio:</strong> 1/√2 for both mappings</li>
    <li><strong>Number of transformations:</strong> 2</li>
    <li><strong>Tiling:</strong> Four Dragon Curves together tile the plane</li>
    <li><strong>Boundary:</strong> The curve is nowhere differentiable</li>
    <li><strong>Constructed by:</strong> John Heighway, NASA (1960s); popularized by Martin Gardner</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>References</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      Gardner, M. (1967). "Mathematical Games." <em>Scientific American</em>, 216(3), 124–125.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dragon_curve" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        Dragon curve — Wikipedia
      </a>
    </li>
  </ul>
</IFSEntryLayout>
